    },
    {
      "overview_item_type": "essential_ideas",
      "overview_item_content_type": "html",
      "overview_item_title": "Essential Ideas",
      "overview_item_data": {
        "overview_item_data_type": "list",
        "overview_item_data_items": [
          "You can use the Quadratic Formula to calculate the solutions to any quadratic.",
          "The quadratic equation coincides with the graphical solution. The solutions relate to the axis of symmetry, <math><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>, and the distance from the axis to the solutions, <math><mfrac><msqrt><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></msqrt><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>.",
          "You can use the discriminant, <math><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math>, to indicate the number of real roots a quadratic equation has.",
          "Adding two rational numbers results in a rational number. Adding a rational number and an irrational number results in an irrational number."
        ]
      }
    },
